<font color="#FF0000">HUMANITY AND THE LACK THEREOF!</font><br>
<tt>Tue Apr 29 19:15:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I would like to come full circle to Liens original question about what we thought of Kim Phuc as portraied in that now infamous photograph.<br><br>
I was more than two years home when that village was napalmed. It was not a photograph when I first saw it, but a film. I had seen it only that one time, but it is a memory that has not eased with the years.<br><br>
I remember the film showing Kim Phuc walking down the road, along with other children of the village. Some were burned as severe as she was, a couple others had their clothes burned off, but others did not. I saw them walk past what had looked like military police. Kim Phuc came closer to the cameraman shooting this film and with Kim Phuc crying, arms stretched out because of the pain, the look of horror on her face, she was looking at each photographer one at a time as if pleading for help, and in doing so, made a complete circle. Then one of the photographers walked up to her face and snapped a picture. Kim Phuc, realizing there was no help to be had, continued down the road, the film showing her walking away from the cameraman.<br><br>
To those M.P.'s and those photographers, I have very little to say other than may you burn in hell and suffer the ten time ten that those combined kids had suffered, on that day and all the days after.  Barring the day you end up in hell, should I ever meet you, be assured that I will gut you from crotch to gullet like a fish.<br><br>
Not one of you had put you cameras aside or stepped in their path to help.
